--   target-code (×1), red-team (×5), harden (×4), verify-patch (×4),
--   spawn-regression-test (×4), regression-test-0 (×1), regression-test-1 (×1),
--   regression-test-2 (×1), regression-test-3 (×1), security-report (×1)
--
-- Total cell evaluations: 23
-- Total LLM calls: 22 (all cells except target-code are soft)
--
-- Key observations:
--
-- ⊢= Observation 1: ⊢⊢ accumulate mode enables monotonic artifact growth
--   Each iteration adds one regression test cell that persists across all future
--   iterations. The wildcard regression-test-*→passes resolves to an ever-growing
--   array: [] → [true] → [true, true] → [true, true, true] → [true, true, true, true].
--   This is the core mechanic: the adversarial loop accumulates constraints. The
--   red-team must find vulnerabilities NOT already tested. The harden step must
--   not break ANY accumulated test. Monotonicity is structural, not aspirational.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 2: guard clauses provide clean ⊢∘ termination
--   When red-team yields vulnerability = "none", the guard `where vulnerability
--   != "none"` on harden, verify-patch, and spawn-regression-test prevents those
--   cells from evaluating. Simultaneously, the guard `where vulnerability = "none"`
--   on security-report enables it. In R16, this gating was implicit in the ⊢∘
--   semantics. In v0.2, guards make it explicit and composable — other cells
--   downstream of security-report could further dispatch on guard conditions.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 3: given? tolerates empty regression test set on iteration 1
--   On the first iteration, no regression-test-* cells exist. Without given?,
--   red-team and harden would block forever on a wildcard that matches nothing.
--   given? resolves ⊥ / empty set to a concrete empty array, allowing iteration 1
--   to proceed. This is the v0.2 pattern for bootstrapping accumulation loops:
--   given? on the first iteration, given on subsequent ones (where at least one
--   match exists). The optional dependency is a seed enabler.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 4: aspirational oracles on ⊢∘-managed cells provide feedback without gating
--   Red-team and harden have multiple ⊨ assertions. Under v0.2, these are
--   aspirational — their failure feeds into the ⊢∘ improvement cycle but does
--   not independently block freezing. This is correct for this program: if
--   red-team's vulnerability description is slightly malformed, the ⊢∘ loop
--   will still proceed, and the next iteration can refine. The until condition
--   (vulnerability = "none") is the true convergence gate, not oracle perfection.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 5: adversarial triage is emergent, not programmed
--   The red-team found vulnerabilities in decreasing severity: critical (KeyError),
--   critical (plaintext passwords), high (no rate limiting), medium (timing
--   side-channel). Nobody told the red-team to prioritize by severity — the
--   prompt says "SINGLE most critical." This natural triage behavior means the
--   most dangerous flaws are fixed first. The 4-round progression from crash
--   bugs to side-channels mirrors real security audits.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 6: verify-patch new-issues[] is a discovery channel
--   In frame 13, verify-patch identified a new issue (in-memory lockout state
--   not shared across processes) that the red-team hadn't found. This is an
--   emergent property of the verify step: it exercises the code differently
--   than the red-team, producing insights the adversarial model missed. In a
--   production Cell runtime, new-issues could feed into a secondary spawner
--   that creates non-blocking advisory cells. The current program doesn't
--   consume new-issues, but the dataflow path exists.
--
-- ⊢= Observation 7: v0.2 features are structurally load-bearing in this program
--   Unlike program 09 (negotiation) where v0.2 was mostly a compliance upgrade,
--   this program genuinely needs v0.2 features: (a) given? is essential for
--   bootstrapping the accumulation loop; (b) guard clauses provide clean
--   bidirectional termination gating (suppress harden when done, enable report
--   when done); (c) accumulate mode on ⊢⊢ is the core mechanism for growing
--   the regression set; (d) wildcard deps are the collection mechanism for
--   spawned test cells. Without v0.2, this program would require ad-hoc
--   workarounds for each of these patterns.
